.TH NETFYR\-DAEMON 8 "" "" "System Manager's Manual"
.SH NAME
netfyr\-daemon \- netfyr network configuration daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B netfyr\-daemon
.SH DESCRIPTION
The netfyr daemon is a long\-running process that manages network
configuration.
It listens on a Varlink socket for policy submissions from the
.BR netfyr (1)
CLI, manages DHCPv4 client lifecycles, monitors for external network
changes, and records all state transitions in a journal.
.PP
The daemon is typically started via systemd:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
systemctl start netfyr
.fi
.RE
.SH "EXTERNAL CHANGE DETECTION"
The daemon monitors the kernel for network state changes made by other
tools (e.g.,
.BR ip (8),
NetworkManager) or by the kernel itself (e.g., carrier loss).
When an external change is detected on a managed interface, the daemon
records a journal entry with trigger type
.I external_change
but does not re\-apply the current desired state.
.PP
Important limitations:
.PP
.B "Only managed interfaces are monitored."
.PP
An interface is
.I managed
when at least one active policy targets it.
If no policies are active, no external changes are detected.
The daemon does not monitor interfaces that have never been the target
of a policy.
.PP
.B "Monitored properties."
.PP
The daemon subscribes to netlink notifications for link attribute
changes (mtu, state, flags) and IPv4 address additions and removals.
Only properties that netfyr manages on ethernet interfaces are tracked.
Changes to properties outside netfyr's scope (e.g., IPv6 addresses,
routing tables, qdiscs) are not detected.
.PP
.B "Debounce window."
.PP
Network changes often arrive in bursts.
The daemon coalesces notifications within a 500ms window into a single
journal entry.
This means there may be a short delay before a change appears in the
journal.
.PP
.B "No automatic re\-reconciliation."
.PP
The daemon records external changes but does not fight back.
To restore the desired state, run
.B "netfyr apply"
or submit policies again.
The next reconciliation cycle (e.g., a DHCP event or policy submission)
will re\-apply the current desired state, which may differ from the
externally modified state.
.SH JOURNAL
The daemon writes all state transitions to an append\-only journal in
NDJSON format.
This includes policy applications, DHCP events, daemon startup,
external changes, and reverts.
.PP
The journal is stored at
.I /var/lib/netfyr/journal/
by default (configurable via
.BR NETFYR_JOURNAL_DIR ).
Use
.BR "netfyr history" (1)
to inspect journal entries and
.BR "netfyr revert" (1)
to restore a previous state.
.PP
Journal files are rotated at 10,000 entries or 50\ MB (configurable via
.B NETFYR_JOURNAL_MAX_ENTRIES
and
.BR NETFYR_JOURNAL_MAX_SIZE ).
Rotated files are gzip\-compressed and retained for 90 days by default
(configurable via
.BR NETFYR_JOURNAL_RETENTION_DAYS ).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NETFYR_SOCKET_PATH
Path to the Varlink socket (default:
.IR /run/netfyr/netfyr.sock ).
.TP
.B NETFYR_POLICY_DIR
Directory for persisted policies (default:
.IR /var/lib/netfyr/policies/ ).
.TP
.B NETFYR_JOURNAL_DIR
Directory for journal files (default:
.IR /var/lib/netfyr/journal/ ).
.TP
.B NETFYR_JOURNAL_MAX_ENTRIES
Maximum entries per journal file before rotation (default: 10000).
.TP
.B NETFYR_JOURNAL_MAX_SIZE
Maximum journal file size in bytes before rotation (default: 52428800).
.TP
.B NETFYR_JOURNAL_RETENTION_DAYS
Days to retain rotated journal archives (default: 90).
.SH "ACCESS CONTROL"
The daemon socket is created with mode 0666 so that any local user can
connect.
.B Read\-only operations
(show, query, history, diagnose, and dry\-run revert) are available to
all users.
.B Write operations
(apply and non\-dry\-run revert) require the connecting process to run as
root (uid\ 0); non\-root clients receive a
.I PermissionDenied
error.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /run/netfyr/netfyr.sock
Varlink socket for CLI\-to\-daemon communication.
.TP
.I /var/lib/netfyr/policies/
Persisted policies that survive daemon restarts.
.TP
.I /var/lib/netfyr/journal/
Journal directory containing
.I current.ndjson
and archived entries.
.TP
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/
User\-provided policy files loaded at startup.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR netfyr (1),
.BR netfyr\-apply (1),
.BR netfyr\-query (1),
.BR netfyr\-history (1),
.BR netfyr\-revert (1),
.BR netfyr.yaml (5),
.BR netfyr\-examples (7),
.BR systemd (1)
